{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"7a464034-63b5-460b-90da-96cc629f2986","content":"PID 12345 doesn't appear to be running on this machine. But here's exactly how to diagnose the runtime and configure dumps when it is running:\n\n---\n\n### 1. Determine CoreCLR vs NativeAOT\n\n```bash\n# Check if libcoreclr.so is loaded — if yes, it's CoreCLR\ngrep -q 'libcoreclr\\.so' /proc/<PID>/maps && echo \"CoreCLR\" || echo \"Likely NativeAOT\"\n\n# Double-check: NativeAOT binaries are fully self-contained, no coreclr\nreadelf -d /proc/<PID>/exe 2>/dev/null | grep -i coreclr\n```\n\nIf `libcoreclr.so` appears in the memory maps → **CoreCLR**. If not → **NativeAOT**.\n\n---\n\n### 2. Configure Crash Dumps\n\n#### For CoreCLR:\n```bash\n# Set environment variables before launching the app:\nexport DOTNET_DbgEnableMiniDump=1\nexport DOTNET_DbgMiniDumpType=4          # 4 = Full heap dump (Triage=1, Mini=2, Heap=3, Full=4)\nexport DOTNET_DbgMiniDumpName=/tmp/dumps/coredump.%p.%t\nmkdir -p /tmp/dumps\n```\n\nCoreCLR has its own built-in crash dump writer that bypasses the kernel's `core_pattern`.\n\n#### For NativeAOT:\nNativeAOT has **no built-in dump writer** — you rely on the OS kernel:\n\n```bash\n# Enable core dumps via kernel\nulimit -c unlimited\necho '/tmp/dumps/core.%p.%t' | sudo tee /proc/sys/kernel/core_pattern\nmkdir -p /tmp/dumps\n\n# If using systemd (which often hijacks core_pattern):\nsudo coredumpctl             # check if systemd-coredump is active\n# Configure /etc/systemd/coredump.conf:\n#   Storage=external\n#   ProcessSizeMax=8G\n#   ExternalSizeMax=8G\n```\n\n---\n\n### 3. Quick Reference\n\n| | **CoreCLR** | **NativeAOT** |\n|---|---|---|\n| Detection | `libcoreclr.so` in maps | No coreclr references |\n| Dump mechanism | Built-in (`DOTNET_DbgEnableMiniDump`) | Kernel core dumps (`core_pattern`) |\n| Analysis tool | `dotnet-dump analyze` | `gdb` / `lldb` |\n\nRun the `grep` command against your actual PID to determine which path to follow, then apply the corresponding config before restarting the app.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"8b9a67e6-ea43-47d7-a2e9-eb1555d1db03","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The process doesn't exist. PID 12345 isn't running. Let me help the user anyway with the general approach — I'll explain how to determine the runtime and configure dumps.","outputTokens":719,"requestId":"6814:163FFF:18739A9:1B8BF79:69FD436E"},"id":"ae5a12c3-2f53-4d75-90d6-a55e40b166e7","timestamp":"2026-05-08T01:59:33.606Z","parentId":"4d58b13d-8d4b-4fc5-a2b8-31647a03c6e1"}
